What is dynamic memory allocation?
Memory allocated during runtime from the heap using:
malloc()
calloc()
realloc()
free()
Example:
int *p = (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));


Difference between stack and heap
Automatic -Stack
Manual Heap
Fast Stack
Slower Heap
Freed automatically Stack
Must call free() Heap
Limited size Stack
Larger size Heap

What does malloc() return?
Returns a void pointer (void*)
Points to the allocated memory block
Returns NULL if allocation fails
int *p = malloc(sizeof(int));


Why do we check for NULL?
if(p == NULL)
{
    printf("Memory allocation failed");
}
If the heap has insufficient memory, malloc() returns NULL. Using a NULL pointer causes undefined behavior.


Difference between malloc() and calloc()
malloc
calloc
One argument (bytes)
Two arguments (count, size)
Memory contains garbage values
Memory initialized to 0
Slightly faster
Slightly slower
int *a = malloc(5 * sizeof(int));
int *b = calloc(5, sizeof(int));

What is realloc()?
Changes the size of an already allocated memory block.
p = realloc(p, 10 * sizeof(int));
May return the same address
May return a new address
Old data is preserved (up to the minimum of old and new sizes)

What happens if realloc() fails?
p = realloc(p, new_size);
If it fails, p becomes NULL and the old memory is lost.
int *temp = realloc(p, new_size);
if(temp != NULL)
{
    p = temp;
}


What is a memory leak?
Memory allocated on the heap but never freed
int *p = malloc(sizeof(int));
// free(p); missing
After the pointer goes out of scope, the memory remains allocated and becomes unreachable.

What is a dangling pointer?
A pointer that points to memory that has already been freed.
int *p = malloc(sizeof(int));

free(p);

*p = 10;   // ❌ Dangling pointer use

Prevention
free(p);
p = NULL;

Difference between memory leak and dangling pointer
Memory Leak
Dangling Pointer
Memory not freed
Memory freed but pointer still used
Wastes memory
Can crash the program
Pointer lost
Pointer still exists

Why is free(NULL) safe?
The C standard guarantees that:
free(NULL);
does nothing. No crash occurs.

What is a double free?
free(p);
free(p);   // ❌
Freeing the same memory block twice causes undefined behavior and may corrupt the heap.
Prevention
free(p);
p = NULL;

Where is dynamically allocated memory stored?
In the heap segment.
The pointer variable itself is usually stored on the stack.
Example:
int *p = malloc(sizeof(int));
Memory:
Stack: p (address)
Heap : allocated int


What is the size of allocated memory?
Trick Question
int *p = malloc(10 * sizeof(int));
printf("%zu", sizeof(p));
Prints 8 on a 64-bit system (pointer size), not 40.
sizeof(p) gives the size of the pointer, not the allocated block.



